Henri Gouges

Not long ago, we were privileged to attend the celebration of the 75th birthday of Henri Gouges, and at that occasion we drank the wines of Nuits-St. Georges produced by his grandfather, then his father, and finally himself. The heritage of this great man, the founder of ‘Appella- tion Controlée’ in Burgundy, is now carried on by his two dedicated sons, Michel and Marcel. We are proud to offer his wines, the best of Nuits, to the Burgundy drinkers of the United States. In an area where a man’s wine prop- erty is measured, row by row, the Gouges Domaine is unique—it culti- vates 23 acres of some of the choic- est wine real estate. When you pull the cork from either of these two wines, you will detect the exception- ally delicious gout de terroir (taste of soil). Because of finesse, ‘les St. Georges’ generally takes the honors as the best wine produced in the commune.

Jean Ponsot

Only last week, we took a bottle of Ponsot’s Clos de la Roche 1966 from our cellars and tasted it. In the com- pany of objective wine authorities, the universal verdict was “one of the greatest red Burgundies we have ever tasted, regardless of price.” And M. Ponsot claims his 1969 is even better! Our advice is to acquire a few bottles of the 1966 while we still have them—judge it——and if you agree, reserve a case of his 1969. Jean Ponsot, unlike most of his neighbors, sticks to old-fashioned methods and simply refuses to de- stem when vinifying his wines—the result is that they are big, deep tannic, slow-maturing and excep- tionally long-lived. This is not only true for Clos de la Roche, but also for his other vineyard holdings in Chambolle-Musigny and Chamber-

Prince de Merode

NOBLE indeed are the wines vini- fied by Prince de Merode, the cousin of King Baudouin of Belgium. His love of the soil and its wines matches despite his regal backgrou nd, the af- fection of his farmer neighbors.

The Merode holdings are in the very best ‘Téte de Cuvée’ vineyards of Aloxe-Corton, crowned by the king of them all—Corton, Clos du Roi— which does not deign to bow its head in deference to any other Cru of the entire Cote d’Or. The Aloxe-Corton, comes from ‘Premier Cru’ holdings, and is superb. Here we are dealing with the longest-lived wines of the Cote de Beaune, exhibiting extraor- dinary breed and texture, amazingly silky and beautiful balance—the best since 1961. Delivery — Spring 1971.

DU ROI Henri Lamarche Mr. Lamarche is to the wine world of Burgundy what Alfred Knopf is to the publishing world—an uncon- tested symbol of uncompromising excellence. His holdings in the great vineyards are astonishing—his cel- lars wind their way, cave after cave, under half the town of Vosne- Romanée. Just gaze at the names shown below — they are emperors

among wines.

Tasting in the cellars of Henri Lamarche.

And the crowning jewel of them all is the tiny 3.3 acre corridor known as ‘La Grande Rue’ which separates La Tache and Romanée-Conti. All of Mr. Lamarche’s wines are long on finesse and style, as the good wines of Vosne-Romanée should be, and are destined to mature with elegant grace. They can be considered among the noblest wines being produced in Burgundy today.
